## Package Overview

`SundusGenome1` is an R package that provides:

| Component | Description |
|---|---|
| **`Genome` (S4 class)** | Stores a genome's name, chromosome count, and protein count |
| **`avgProteinPerCh()`** | Computes the average proteins per chromosome (rounded to nearest integer) |

---

## How to Install from GitHub

### Step 1 – Install the `devtools` package (do this once)

Open R or RStudio and run:

```r
install.packages("devtools")
```

### Step 2 – Install `SundusGenome1` directly from GitHub

```r
library(devtools)
install_github("sundusjasim897-boop/SundusGenome1")
```

### Step 3 – Load the package

```r
library(SundusGenome1)
```

---

## How to Use the Package

### 1. Create a `Genome` object

Use `new()` to create an instance of the `Genome` S4 class.  
The class has three slots:

| Slot | Type | Description |
|---|---|---|
| `genome_name` | character | Name of the genome |
| `total_chromosomes` | numeric | Total number of chromosomes |
| `total_proteins` | numeric | Total number of proteins |

```r
# Example 1 – Human genome
human <- new("Genome",
             genome_name       = "Human",
             total_chromosomes = 23,
             total_proteins    = 20000)

# Example 2 – Mouse genome
mouse <- new("Genome",
             genome_name       = "Mouse",
             total_chromosomes = 20,
             total_proteins    = 22000)
```

### 2. Access slot values

```r
human@genome_name        # "Human"
human@total_chromosomes  # 23
human@total_proteins     # 20000
```

### 3. Call `avgProteinPerCh()`

```r
avgProteinPerCh(human)   # returns 870
avgProteinPerCh(mouse)   # returns 1100
```

The method computes:

```
round( total_proteins / total_chromosomes )
```

---

## Full Working Example

```r
library(devtools)
install_github("sundusjasim897-boop/SundusGenome1")
library(SundusGenome1)

# Create genome objects
human <- new("Genome",
             genome_name       = "Human",
             total_chromosomes = 23,
             total_proteins    = 20000)

ecoli <- new("Genome",
             genome_name       = "E. coli",
             total_chromosomes = 1,
             total_proteins    = 4300)

# Compute averages
avgProteinPerCh(human)   # 870
avgProteinPerCh(ecoli)   # 4300
```

